{"id":"1307.3844","submitter":"Stephane Regnier","authors":"S. Regnier","title":"Magnetic Field Extrapolations in the Corona: Success and Future\n  Improvements","comments":"Accepted in Solar Physics","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/s11207-013-0367-8","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.SR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The solar atmosphere being magnetic in nature, the understanding of the\nstructure and evolution of the magnetic field in different regions of the solar\natmosphere has been an important task over the past decades. This task has been\nmade complicated by the difficulties to measure the magnetic field in the\ncorona, while it is currently known with a good accuracy in the photosphere\nand/or chromosphere. Thus, to determine the coronal magnetic field, a\nmathematical method has been developed based on the observed magnetic field.\nThis is the so-called magnetic field extrapolation technique. This technique\nrelies on two crucial points: (i) the physical assumption leading to the system\nof differential equations to be solved, (ii) the choice and quality of the\nassociated boundary conditions. In this review, I summarise the physical\nassumptions currently in use and the findings at different scales in the solar\natmosphere. I concentrate the discussion on the extrapolation techniques\napplied to solar magnetic data and the comparison with observations in a broad\nrange of wavelengths (from hard X-rays to radio emission).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 15 Jul 2013 07:55:31 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 16 Jul 2013 16:52:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-16"}
